A film by @type7

Son of legendary Australian shaper and surfer Neal Purchase, Neal Purchase Jnr was more or less born into the profession and culture. Growing up competing, Neal found his way as a free surfer, later following his father’s footsteps as a shaper. Now, Neal is renowned internationally for his surfing ability as well as his craftsmanship.

His iconic Duo, Quartet and Single fin shapes are a modern day homage to the past, something he credits to his father’s influence. An ever evolving refinement of classic designs, Neal’s boards are just as much a work of art as they are high performance surf craft. 

Yet despite his status in the surf world, 'Purcho' is one of the most kind, humble people you will meet. In fact, he scored the soundtrack for this very film 🏄‍♂️

Directed by @caplice
Starring @nealpurchasejnr
Production Company @mojaveproductions
Produced by @harrisonamark
Director Of Photography @andygough_

Special thanks to @lemac_australia & @filmstock_aust

There’s a special feeling in the air whenever you’re at a circuit and an orange race car is tearing around, and it’s all thanks to the brilliant branding of Jägermeister, who since 1972 have adorned their sponsored cars with a livery that’s impossible to miss. 

We’re rapidly approaching their 50th anniversary, and what better time is there to celebrate their legacy than now. Our friends at @cdworkscreative have linked up with the company to create a single point to explore their incredible history at @rennmeister72, and have kicked it off with a photo shoot with our forever favourite @stephan_bauer at Kraftwerk in Berlin that we just had to share with you all 🏭

node.text:
Nestled among the jungle trees of Southern Mexico, this is the Aviv House by Co-lab (@colab_tulum). More than anything, this house is a triumph of texture, an often overlooked element with the power to make just about any design exciting. The forms of this house are very simple, you might even imagine you could come up with them yourself. In fact, with a decent understanding of spacial design, you probably could. The hard work is done in the material selection.

Everything from soft the fabrics to the stone floors has been put together to work in unison. They say all the furnishings were designed in house or in close collaboration with local artisans and despite the almost mathematical precision of the individual elements, everything exudes a human quality. It’s a closed system, like a smartphone or a sports car, it deceives you with its simplicity because an effort has been made to hide effort in itself. In works like this the job of the designer is to disappear completely. The height of praise, paradoxically, is to never be noticed in the first place.

Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7
Photos by César Bijar

“Mulholland to Old Topanga is on my commute and the 912 was definitely built for those roads,” Steven Lindenfelser (@stevenlindenfelser) explains. “I love the feeling of an air cooled motor knocking around the back seat, so I sought the same from a motorcycle.”

The term ‘airhead’ had been shared with me at car meets. I soon found out that in the moto world it only applies to one kind of bike, an air cooled R Series. I started looking for builders who could source a bike for me and I fell into the lap of Bobby Sabel at @Roughchild. I knew immediately that he understood what I was looking for.

Bobby knows his stuff - he might not admit it, but he’s a purist at heart. He convinced me to match the bike to the Porsche, which I’m so happy he did because the theme looks incredible on the bike. We did a black leather saddle to match the car, brown grips to match the steering wheel, olive paint all over and even a custom speedometer with an orange needle to match the Porsche's dials. The bike rides as good as it looks. Bored to 1000cc, twin sparked, geared for revs, it’s the perfect canyon runner.”

node.text:
At garden designer Arne Maynard (@arnemaynardgardendesign)’s home Allt y Bella, the garden is as functional as the farmhouse. Vegetable patches, nut trees, and orchards co-exist in the grounds, and in theory you could live very well off the land here. The more decorative plants are in homage to the five storey tower, a seventeenth century extension of the house almost certainly built as something of a folly. The garden therefore has a direct relationship with the house, mimicking both its practicalities and its extravagances.

In an excerpt of his book, Arne says this of Allt y Bela's current state; “When I first saw the garden, I said the house was like and exotic pearl sitting on a cushion of green velvet, and now we’ve embroidered the cushion with native and species plants. The topiary is the Elizabethan stump work on the cushion, and my rarities are the occasional golden threads that give it another dimension. It is all very delicately crafted, all hand-stitched.”

Photos and words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

node.text:
“Plants are my brush strokes,” garden designer Arne Maynard (@arnemaynardgardendesign) explains of his world-leading artistry. Nature is his medium, and Arne seems immune to the error that many other designers make in assuming human creativity is best directed at the exile of nature. Foliage is as core to his work as steel and plastic is to others. At his home, Allt y Bela, the garden is his architecture.

The building itself is a medieval farmhouse, which exists largely in its own time-warp state. The only feature that lends it modernity is the landscape design around it. It’s not the only thing that could have been done to achieve this, we’ve seen a number of similar period houses updated with steel and glass that reach a very convincing “old meets new” feel. This is ‘soft’ design however, totally sustainable and endlessly reconfigurable.

Photos and words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

“Both are 1969, both a match for one another. I now have the perfect pair of machines to make every day commutes feel like a chase scene from a spy thriller.”

Steven Lindenfelser (@stevenlindenfelser) is an airhead to the core. For once, that’s not a pejorative. His garage, a 912 and a hand built @roughchild bike are the stuff of dreams. It’s rare you get a duo to match this well while ticking such a broad set of boxes.

“The 912 came first,” he explains. “I asked a dealer to look for one in any shade of green and they came through with a car in olive. It was a love at first sight moment. The interior had been fabulously restored, the only thing I added was a wood wheel. However, it didn’t run as well as it looked. It had some Dellorto carbs that I immediately swapped for Webers. The motor had a small leak in one side so I swapped to higher compression pistons when it was repaired. 912 legend John Benton (@bentonperformance) did all the work, now it’s a daily driver.”

Photos by @jrhebertphoto
